Stock Count (Physical Stock Take) module
Context
Company does periodic (monthly/quarterly/ad-hoc) physical stock counts to reconcile physical vs. system stock, then needs the difference posted as a Stock Adjustment (existing module, migration 076). Two-screen workflow: Screen 1 — one or more counters each do a physical count at a location (filtered by category/item-type) and save/submit their own count entry. Screen 2 — a manager picks multiple submitted counts for the same location, sees them "clubbed" (summed) per product/batch/serial against system stock, reviews the variance, and approves — which posts a real Stock Adjustment through the existing posting engine.

Design decisions already made with the user (do not re-litigate):

Blind count — Screen 1 never shows system/expected qty to the counter, to avoid biasing the physical count.
Variance basis = system stock AS OF a chosen date, computed live from ril_stock_ledger (immutable, append-only, already the schema's sole source of truth) — not a live read of rim_product_location.current_stock. Stays correct even if counting spans days or the manager reviews long after counting.
Scan behavior: scanning a barcode/part number jumps to and highlights that row in the pre-populated worksheet; counter then types the qty (not a tally-increment-per-scan mode).
Unknown serial (physically found, system has no ledger history for it at this location): flagged as an exception, excluded from auto-adjustment entirely — never auto-create a + line with no established cost/origin.
Other load-bearing decisions made during design (see full reasoning in research/plan below — these are not optional variants, they're the correct shape given the codebase's own precedents):

Uncounted ≠ counted-zero. An item in scope that nobody entered a qty for must be completely excluded from variance — never treated as physical-zero. Enforced via an explicit is_counted flag per line (not just nullable qty), because for batch/serial-tracked products "confirmed empty" and "never touched" both look like zero children.
Never merge same-product quantities at write time (confirmed codebase-wide convention across Purchase Bill←GRNs, GRN←POs, Material Issue←Requisitions — none of them merge; they keep one row per source-document reference and compute clubbed totals via a query at read time). Screen 2 stores only which submitted counts it includes (a junction table); the clubbed variance itself is computed on-the-fly by a shared SQL function, never written as a merged copy.
Reuse the existing Stock Adjustment engine, don't reimplement it. Screen 2's Approve computes netted +/- lines and calls the existing fn_save_stock_adjustment + fn_approve_stock_adjustment (migration 076) — inheriting cost-lookup, GL posting, and the batch/serial negative-stock rules for free, per the project's absolute "shared posting engines" rule.
Reservation-once-consumed, mirroring GRN's billed_invoice_no pattern: a submitted count picked into a manager's DRAFT review is locked from being picked into a second concurrent review.
Backend — two new migrations
backend/migrations/078_stock_count.sql (Screen 1)
rim_voucher_types: seed ('CNT', 'Stock Count', 'STOCK', NULL, 'YEARLY', 'CNT/{LOC}/{YYYY}/{SEQ5}', true) — numbering only, no posting (same shape as Opening Stock's OPST).

rih_stock_count_headers: id, client_id, company_id, location_id, count_no, count_date, category_filter_id → rim_item_categories(id) [nullable = all], nature_filter TEXT [nullable = all, matches rim_products.product_nature's CHECK values], status CHECK IN ('DRAFT','SUBMITTED','CONSOLIDATED'), submitted_by, submitted_at, consolidated_into_review_no, consolidated_into_review_date [reservation pointer], remarks, <standard audit columns>. UNIQUE(client_id, company_id, count_no, count_date). auth_rw_* RLS, updated_at trigger.

rid_stock_count_lines: one row per counted PRODUCT (not per lot — the worksheet is pre-populated by filter, one row per in-scope product; batch/serial detail hangs off that row via the existing generic rid_transaction_line_batches/rid_transaction_line_serials tables, source_doc_type='STOCK_COUNT', line_serial = rid_stock_count_lines.serial_no — confirmed schema: both tables key on client_id, company_id, source_doc_type, source_doc_no, source_doc_date, line_serial, batches additionally carry batch_no, expiry_date, qty_pack, qty_loose, base_qty, serials carry serial_no). Columns: id, client_id, company_id, count_no, count_date, serial_no INT, product_id, uom_id, uom_conversion_factor, is_counted BOOLEAN NOT NULL DEFAULT false [authoritative "row touched" flag], counted_qty_pack, counted_qty_loose, counted_base_qty [all NULL unless is_counted=true; for batch/serial rows base_qty = SUM(children)], barcode [audit: which scan matched this row], remarks, <standard audit columns>. CHECK (is_counted=false AND counted_base_qty IS NULL) OR is_counted=true. UNIQUE(..., count_no, count_date, serial_no). FK to header. auth_rw_* RLS.

Divergence from Stock Adjustment's use of the batch/serial tables: Stock Adjustment's - line shows an existing-lot candidate picker. Stock Count's batch/serial entry must be pure free-text new-lot entry (GRN-style — counter types what they physically found), regardless of whether the system already knows that lot. Showing "expected" candidates would leak system data into what must stay a blind count.

fn_stock_count_eligible_products(p_client_id, p_company_id, p_category_id DEFAULT NULL, p_nature DEFAULT NULL) RETURNS TABLE(product_id, product_code, product_name, tracking_type, base_uom_id, uom_label, barcode, part_number) — SQL STABLE, filters rim_products by is_active/is_deleted, category_id IN (SELECT id FROM fn_category_subtree(p_category_id)) when given (first Flutter caller of this existing-but-unconsumed function), product_nature = p_nature when given. Called once, when the counter confirms Location+Date+filters and hits "Start Count" — Flutter builds the initial is_counted=false row set from this, then the first fn_save_stock_count persists that snapshot. Resuming a draft never re-runs this — it reads rid_stock_count_lines directly, which is what makes the worksheet's scope fixed at creation.

fn_save_stock_count(p_header, p_lines, p_batches, p_serials, p_user_id) RETURNS TEXT — DRAFT-only, same shape/delete-reinsert pattern as fn_save_stock_adjustment (076). p_lines is the FULL worksheet on every save (not incremental). Per counted line with batch children: sum-check abs(batch_qty_sum - counted_base_qty) > 0.0001 → RAISE EXCEPTION 'BATCH_QTY_MISMATCH'.

fn_submit_stock_count(p_client_id, p_company_id, p_count_no, p_count_date, p_user_id) RETURNS VOID — locks DRAFT→SUBMITTED. Blocks with NO_COUNTED_LINES if zero rows have is_counted=true. No fn_check_period_open/fn_check_backdate_allowed call — Screen 1 never touches the ledger or GL; those checks belong entirely to Screen 2's Approve.

Menu seed: IN-CNT / "Stock Count" / /inventory/stock-count, approve_allowed=true (gates the Submit button, same convention as every other lock-transition), serial_no 8, group IN-OPS/Operations — into both a direct existing-companies INSERT (migration 078, mirrors migration 071's pattern) and fn_seed_client_modules.sql's IN block (future clients).

backend/migrations/079_stock_count_review.sql (Screen 2)
Additive traceability on the existing Stock Adjustment table (mirrors rih_finance_headers.source_doc_type/no/date from migration 037, which Stock Adjustment's own header currently lacks):

ALTER TABLE rih_stock_adjustment_headers
    ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS source_doc_type TEXT,
    ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS source_doc_no   TEXT,
    ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS source_doc_date DATE;
fn_save_stock_adjustment (076) gets CREATE OR REPLACEd — same 5-param signature — to also persist these three from optional header JSONB keys. The manual Stock Adjustment screen is unaffected (never sends those keys, they stay NULL).

rim_voucher_types: seed ('CNTR', 'Stock Count Review', 'STOCK', NULL, 'YEARLY', 'CNTR/{LOC}/{YYYY}/{SEQ5}', true) — numbering only. (The actual GL/stock posting happens entirely inside the existing ADJ/ADJV codes via the composed call below.)

rih_stock_count_review_headers: id, client_id, company_id, location_id, review_no, review_date, as_of_date DATE NOT NULL [the ONE canonical variance-comparison date, manager-set, defaults to today], reason_id → rim_common_masters [STOCK_ADJUSTMENT_REASON type — reuse the existing 'Physical Count Variance' row seeded in 076, no new common-master seed needed], status CHECK IN ('DRAFT','APPROVED'), approved_by, approved_at, posted_adjustment_no, posted_adjustment_date, remarks, <standard audit columns>. UNIQUE(client_id, company_id, review_no, review_date). auth_rw_* RLS, updated_at trigger.

rid_stock_count_review_sources (junction, membership only — never a merged-line copy, per the "never merge at write time" convention): id, client_id, company_id, review_no, review_date, source_count_no, source_count_date, created_at, created_by. UNIQUE(..., review_no, review_date, source_count_no, source_count_date). FK to review header.

fn_save_stock_count_review(p_header, p_source_refs, p_user_id) RETURNS TEXT — DRAFT-only. Reservation pattern copied exactly from fn_save_purchase_invoice's GRN-reservation logic: on re-save, first un-reserves whatever the draft previously held (rih_stock_count_headers.status back to SUBMITTED, consolidated_into_review_no/date cleared) and clears old junction rows; then for each p_source_refs entry, locks one row per statement in a fixed sort order (deadlock-avoidance rule — ORDER BY source_count_no, source_count_date, SELECT ... FOR UPDATE per row, never a single ORDER BY ... FOR UPDATE), validates status != 'DRAFT' (must be SUBMITTED first) and same location_id, blocks if already reserved by a different review, then sets status='CONSOLIDATED' + reservation pointer and inserts the junction row.

fn_compute_stock_count_variance(p_client_id, p_company_id, p_review_no, p_review_date) RETURNS TABLE(product_id, tracking_type, batch_no, expiry_date, serial_no, counted_qty, system_qty, variance_qty, adjust_flag, is_unknown_serial, unit_cost) — the single source of truth for netting, called by BOTH the on-screen preview grid and Approve, so what the manager sees is guaranteed to be what gets posted. STABLE function:

Builds all_counts from three CTEs over rid_stock_count_lines (is_counted=true only — this is where "uncounted excluded" falls out for free, untouched rows never enter this set) joined through the review's rid_stock_count_review_sources:
untracked: SUM(counted_base_qty) GROUP BY product_id — additive across sources (same product counted in different, non-overlapping zones by different counters).
batch: SUM(base_qty) GROUP BY product_id, batch_no — additive, same reasoning.
serial: SELECT DISTINCT product_id, serial_no — not summed; the same physical unit found in two overlapping counts is one unit, never double-counted.
Computes system_qty per bucket via SUM(ril_stock_ledger.qty_change) WHERE location_id=... AND trans_date <= as_of_date, split three ways (aggregate/batch_no/serial_no — confirmed exact column names against ril_stock_ledger: client_id, company_id, location_id, product_id, trans_date, qty_change, batch_no, serial_no).
adjust_flag: +/-/NULL (NULL = exact match, no line — or unknown serial, see next). is_unknown_serial = (serial_no IS NOT NULL AND system_qty <= 0) — batch gets normal +/- treatment (a never-before-seen batch found physically is a legitimate +, same as Stock Adjustment already allows); only serial gets the exception treatment, per decision #4.
unit_cost is informational only for the preview grid — fn_approve_stock_adjustment re-fetches the real cost itself under row lock, unchanged.
fn_approve_stock_count_review(p_client_id, p_company_id, p_review_no, p_review_date, p_approved_by) RETURNS TEXT (returns the posted adjustment_no):

Lock header, validate DRAFT, validate reason_id IS NOT NULL.
fn_check_period_open/fn_check_backdate_allowed('STOCK_COUNT_REVIEW', as_of_date) + FUTURE_DATE_NOT_ALLOWED guard on as_of_date — same convention as every other Approve function.
Lock every source count (one row per statement, fixed sort order).
Loop fn_compute_stock_count_variance(...): skip is_unknown_serial rows (count them for the error message), skip adjust_flag IS NULL (zero variance), else build one JSONB line per row into p_lines/p_batches/p_serials arrays shaped exactly like fn_save_stock_adjustment expects (qty_pack=qty_loose=0/base_qty=abs(variance_qty) split per pack/loose convention, adjust_flag, reason_id from the review header, remarks referencing the review).
If zero lines produced → RAISE EXCEPTION 'NO_VARIANCE_LINES' (mentioning how many unknown-serial exceptions were skipped, if any).
Compose the existing engine — v_adjustment_no := fn_save_stock_adjustment(header_with_source_doc_tags, lines, batches, serials, p_approved_by); PERFORM fn_approve_stock_adjustment(...). Never write ril_stock_ledger/rid_finance_lines directly.
Mark review APPROVED, store posted_adjustment_no/date.
Menu seed: IN-CNR / "Stock Count Review" / /inventory/stock-count-review, serial_no 9, same group — both places, same pattern as IN-CNT above.

Voucher-code summary
Code	Purpose	Posts GL/stock?
CNT	Numbers Screen 1 documents	No
CNTR	Numbers Screen 2 documents	No
ADJ	(existing) Numbers the auto-created Stock Adjustment	No
ADJV	(existing) Posts the GL entries	Yes — reused unchanged
No new ril_stock_ledger.trans_type value is introduced — Screen 2 only ever reaches the ledger indirectly through fn_approve_stock_adjustment, which already posts ADJUSTMENT_IN/ADJUSTMENT_OUT (whitelisted since migration 036, confirmed in both ril_stock_ledger CHECK constraints already). No CHECK-constraint migration needed.

